  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Where can I get an explainer video for $100?",
  "response": "Getting an explainer video for $100 is possible, but it depends on the quality, length, and complexity you\u2019re looking for. Here are some options where you might find affordable explainer videos at that price point:\n\n### 1. **Freelance Platforms**\n   - **Fiverr**: Many freelancers on Fiverr offer basic explainer video services starting at $100. Look for gigs with good reviews and samples of their work.\n   - **Upwork**: Post your project on Upwork and set your budget to $100. Freelancers will bid on your project, and you can choose the best fit.\n\n### 2. **Online Marketplaces**\n   - **Envato Elements**: While not custom, you can find pre-made explainer video templates for about $16/month (with a subscription). You can customize them yourself using software like After Effects.\n   - **Videezy**: Offers free and paid explainer video templates that you can edit.\n\n### 3. **DIY Tools**\n   - **Animaker**: A user-friendly tool that lets you create explainer videos yourself. Plans start at $10/month, and you can create videos within your budget.\n   - **Powtoon**: Another easy-to-use platform for creating animated explainer videos. Plans start at $15/month.\n   - **Canva**: Offers free and paid video templates that you can customize for simple explainer videos.\n\n### 4. **Social Media and Networking**\n   - **Instagram/TikTok**: Reach out to small creators or animators who might be willing to create a short explainer video for $100.\n   - **Reddit**: Check subreddits like r/forhire or r/slavelabour, where freelancers offer services at competitive rates.\n\n### 5. **Student or Beginner Services**\n   - **Art Schools or Universities**: Contact local art or design schools. Students may be willing to create a video for $100 to build their portfolio.\n   - **Online Communities**: Platforms like Discord or Behance may have beginners offering affordable services.\n\n### Tips for Keeping Costs Low:\n- Keep the video short (30 seconds to 1 minute).\n- Use basic animation or stock assets instead of custom illustrations.\n- Provide a clear script and storyboard to save time for the creator.\n- Avoid complex revisions or high-end production quality.\n\nWhile $100 is on the lower end, you can still find decent options if you\u2019re flexible and do some research!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
